name: Palace Gardens
description: Palace Gardens at Colonial Williamsburg are a beautifully restored, well-tended collection of ornamental and functional 18th‑century gardens behind the Governor’s Palace, featuring a hedge maze, tree tunnel walkways, shaded paths, a pond with turtles, and arbor tunnels. Visitors can explore multiple areas including an Icehouse, with guides bringing history to life and benches for rest. The gardens are lovingly maintained year‑round and glow during the CW Lights night program, making for a magical evening. The hedge maze is a crowd‑pleaser and a fun, quick challenge for families. Pro tip: park on the street by Mathew Whaley School and take the side path on the right of the building to the Governors petite maison for easy access.

name: Crim Dell Bridge
description: Crim Dell Bridge is a charming, historic footbridge tucked within William and Mary College’s campus. Built in 1966 for a student day celebration, it features the iconic love locks and is flanked by benches in a peaceful, wooded setting with clear water, turtles, and good photo opportunities. The nearby reclining-student sculptures and the legend that couples who kiss at the crest will stay together add a romantic, storybook vibe, making it popular for proposals and engagement photos. Some visitors note it feels a bit hidden or more of a nice detour than a destination for a family outing. The area is picturesque in all seasons, though water conditions can vary, so it’s best enjoyed as a brief, serene break from campus life.

description: College Landing Park is a small, tranquil waterfront park with parking, benches, and trashcans, offering nice water views and a pier that extends into the reeds. It’s a popular launch point for kayaks, canoes, and SUPs, and is great for birdwatching, fishing, crabbing, and sunset viewing along College Creek to the James River. The setting is peaceful and scenic, ideal for a picnic or a quiet read, though there isn’t much else beyond the water activities. Be mindful of tides near the bridge, as water can be very shallow at low tide. You may spot crabs, skinks, and other wildlife, reflecting the park’s historic port heritage.

name: Redoubt Park
description: Redoubt Park in Williamsburg is a small, historic site featuring Redoubt #1 and Redoubt #2 with a short paved route and a longer rugged dirt trail (Tuttle Trail). The paved section is brief and not stroller-friendly, while the dirt trail offers a moderate hike with stairs, roots, and various inclines. Interpretive signs tie the site to Civil War history and Quarterpath Road, and the park is dog-friendly, suitable for a quick walk, a family outing, or a longer workout. Trail conditions can be muddy or slippery, and access roads may have potholes; a park bridge has sustained damage from a past fire. Some reviewers note safety concerns in the area, so visitors may want to go with a companion or stay aware of their surroundings.

name: St. George Tucker House
description: St. George Tucker House is a beautiful historic colonial home in Williamsburg, tucked between the Governor’s Mansion and the courthouse. Open primarily to Colonial Williamsburg donors, it serves as a private lounge and learning space where you can rest, have hot drinks, and enjoy light snacks away from the crowds. Six days a week it hosts intimate programs with interpreters and nation builders, including 45-minute talks on life in Colonial Williamsburg and performances or monologues by figures like Thomas Jefferson and George Washington. Visitors consistently praise the welcoming volunteers and the warm hospitality, with notable talks by Edith Cumbo and others. It’s a hub for donor-driven programs and small-group presentations in a charming, private setting.

name: Bassett Trace Nature Trail
description: Bassett Trace Nature Trail is a shaded, forested out-and-back trail located near Colonial Williamsburg, tucked behind Bassett Hall off Francis Street. The route runs about 3 miles round trip (roughly 1.4 miles one-way) with gentle to moderate hills, tree roots, streams, and quaint wooden bridges, and it’s well-marked with interpretive plant and bird signage. It’s a popular spot for hiking, birding, and dog-walking, with benches and occasional detours posted when restoration work is underway. Parking can be limited, with spots near the Griffin Hotel area and a larger public lot on Francis Street. The trail isn’t fully wheelchair-accessible in places due to hills, so wear sturdy shoes and be prepared for mud after rain.

name: Colonial Williamsburg Silversmith
description: Colonial Williamsburg Silversmith is a working workshop and shop on Duke of Gloucester Street where master silversmiths demonstrate the craft—from ingot to finished bowls—and the shop produces much of the silverware you see around Williamsburg. Inside, a display case near the door shows original pieces, while the rest of the space features newer, on-site crafted items and jewelry. Visitors can watch artisans at work, learn about 18th-century tools and techniques, and ask questions as they observe history come to life. Items are available for purchase, including silverware, spoons, and jewelry such as rings and wedding bands. It’s a highlight of a Colonial Williamsburg visit with informative demonstrations, though the level of activity can vary by day.
